#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/lean-startup/references/assumptions.md
M|references|Every startup is built on a stack of unproven assumptions. Most founders treat these assumptions as facts. The Lean Startup treats them as hypotheses that must be tested systematically. Leap-of-faith 
M|references|The two most critical assumptions for any new product:
M|references|Tests whether the product delivers value to customers once they start using it.
M|references|**Core question:** Do customers find this product valuable enough to keep using it (and eventually pay for it)?
M|references|| Dimension | What to Validate | Example Signals |
M|references||-----------|-----------------|-----------------|
M|references|| Problem existence | The problem is real and painful enough to motivate action | Customers describe the problem unprompted in interviews |
M|references|| Solution fit | Your specific solution addresses the problem effectively | Users complete core tasks successfully; retention is strong |
M|references|| Willingness to pay | Customers value the solution enough to exchange money for it | Pre-orders, paid pilots, conversion from free to paid |
M|references|| Frequency | Customers need the solution repeatedly, not just once | Return usage within expected timeframe |
M|references|Tests how new customers discover and adopt the product.
M|references|**Core question:** How will this product spread from early adopters to a broader market?
M|references|| Dimension | What to Validate | Example Signals |
M|references||-----------|-----------------|-----------------|
M|references|| Discoverability | Target customers can find the product | Organic search traffic, word-of-mouth referrals |
M|references|| Acquisition cost | You can acquire customers at a sustainable cost | CAC below projected LTV |
M|references|| Virality | Existing users bring in new users | Viral coefficient, referral rates, soc sharing |
M|references|| Market size | Enough potential customers exist | TAM analysis validated by early traction patterns |
M|references|**Critical insight:** Validate the value hypothesis before the growth hypothesis. Growing something people do not value is the most expensive way to fail.
M|references|Brainstorm every assumption your business relies on. Use these categories as prompts:
M|references|**Customer assumptions:**
M|references|- Our target customer is [specific persona]
M|references|- They experience [specific problem]
M|references|- They currently solve it by [current alternative]
M|references|- They are dissatisfied with the current solution because [reason]
M|references|**Problem assumptions:**
M|references|- The problem is frequent enough to justify a solution
M|references|- The problem is painful enough that people will pay to solve it
M|references|- The problem is not adequately solved by existing alternatives
M|references|**Solution assumptions:**
M|references|- Our solution effectively addresses the problem
M|references|- Customers can use our solution without extensive training
M|references|- The solution is significantly better than alternatives
M|references|**Business model assumptions:**
M|references|- Customers will pay [price] for this solution
M|references|- We can acquire customers for less than [amount]
M|references|- Customer lifetime value exceeds acquisition cost
M|references|- Our market is large enough to build a viable business
M|references|**tec assumptions:**
M|references|- We can build this technology with our team
M|references|- The technology can scale to serve our target market
M|references|- Performance will meet customer expectations
M|references|Plot each assumption on a 2x2 matrix:
M|references|```
M|references|HIGH IMPACT
M|references||
M|references|TEST FIRST     |     MONITOR
M|references|(High Impact,     |  (High Impact,
M|references|High Uncertainty) |   Low Uncertainty)
M|references||
M|references|HIGH UNCERTAINTY -----+------ LOW UNCERTAINTY
M|references||
M|references|EXPLORE        |      IGNORE
M|references|(Low Impact,      |   (Low Impact,
M|references|High Uncertainty) |   Low Uncertainty)
M|references||
M|references|LOW IMPACT
M|references|```
M|references|**Test First (top-left):** These are your leap-of-faith assumptions. If wrong, the business fails. And you have little evidence they are true. Test these immediately.
M|references|**Monitor (top-right):** Important but you have reasonable evidence. Keep an eye on them but do not spend experiment cycles here yet.
M|references|**Explore (bottom-left):** Uncertain but not critical. Explore casually through customer conversations.
M|references|**Ignore (bottom-right):** Low impact and well-understood. Move on.
M|references|For a more structured approach, score each assumption:
M|references|| Assumption | Impact (1-5) | Uncertainty (1-5) | Priority Score | Test Order |
M|references||-----------|-------------|-------------------|---------------|------------|
